\begin_layout Section
Climate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Victoria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Victoria's climate is greatly influenced by its topography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 The Great Dividing Range (GDR), has created three main climatic zones:
 northern, southern and southeastern Victoria.
 In northern Victoria, precipitation is influenced by northwesterly air
 masses.
 The north-west region of this climatic zone receives an annual average
 of 250 to 300 mm of precipitation and endures intense heatwaves; whereas,
 in the north-east the precense of mountains raises the precitation range
 to 800-1000 mm in a year.
 Precipitation in southern Victoria also increases with altitude; however,
 westerly winds drive its formation.
 In contrast, variations in temperature in this zone are driven by northerly
 winds, which produce summers with average air temperature of 28 ºC and
 maxima of 43 ºC.
 In southeastern Victoria, synoptic systems in the Tasman Sea influence
 its precipitation rate, especially in the eastern region that recieves
 in average 1000 mm in a year.
 The western region of southeastern Victoria is less influenced by the Tasman
 Sea, and receives in average 600 mm of precipitation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ecuador
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Tropical Andes climate has several drivers.
 The Amazon forest, oceanic currents, and the topography are among the main
 drivers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martinez2011"

\end_inset

.
 The Amazon forest—through Evapo-transpiration—produces a great amount of
 water vapor.
 This water precipitates along the western Cordillera because of an orographic
 precipitation process.
 This precipitation is also produced in the eastern Cordillera.
 Air masses advected from the Pacific Ocean produce this effect.
 The influence of the Pacific Ocean in the climate variability is important.
 The Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) is the main driver of decadal climate
 variability in this region 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martinez2011"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the inter-annual variability depends on the El Niño
 Southern Oscillation (ENSO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vuille1999,Villacis2003,Martinez2011"

\end_inset

.
 These influences create several climate regions within the Andes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the Ecuadorian Andes—between 1500 to 3000 m—have a “Semi-Humid Mesotherm
al” climate (Pourrut 1995).
 Mean temperatures in this region range from 8 oc to 20 oc.
 Maximum temperatures span from 22 oC and 30 oC.
 Minimum temperatures range from -4 oc to 5 oC.
 Air masses from the Pacific Ocean and the Amazon region create three seasons
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pourrut1995"

\end_inset

.
 Two wet seasons during the periods February-May and October-November.
 A dry season spans from June to September.
 Total annual precipitation ranges from 800 mm to 1500 mm along the Andes.
 Relative humidity varies from 65 to 85 percent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fire
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Victoria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ecuador
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wildfires mostly occur in three geographical regions of Ecuador.
 The Andean region has large extensions of introduced Eucalyptus forests
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Anchaluisa2013"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, the availability of fuels makes it the most wildfire-prone region.
 The fire season in the Ecuadorian Andes spans from July to November 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, the most critical months are July, August and September 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012,SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 The coast and the Galapagos Islands experience wildfire episodes from January
 to May 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wildfires produce severe impacts in Ecuador.
 Yet, information about these impacts is scarce and disperse.
 Wildfires produced 21.570 Ha of area burnt in Ecuador in 2012 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 The Metropolitan District of Quito (MDQ) is particularly vulnerable to
 wildfires.
 The vulnerability is high because 15.4 percent of the national population
 lives here.
 Additionally, vegetation covers 60.46 percent of its territory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Wildfires destroyed 2700 Ha of the MDQ vegetation in 2009 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012"

\end_inset

.
 In 2012, the area burnt by wildfires increased to 4.882,16 Ha 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 This wildfire season cost the MDQ more than 50 million dollars 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, wildfires in Ecuador are anthropogenic in nature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, the MDQ reported that humans cause 95 percent of wildfires in
 the city 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Burning forests to convert them to agricultural use is the main cause of
 wildfires in the country 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013,SecretariadeAmbiente2013,Rodas2015"

\end_inset

.
 Forcing land use changes for urbanization purposes is another reason people
 start wildfires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Rural communities burn agricultural waste, which is a traditional practice
 that fosters wildfire occurrences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012"

\end_inset

.
 Rural people also burn regular waste because of the lack of waste management
 services 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, wildfires occur because of the damaging acts of arsonists 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013,SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bushfire weather
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Meteorological variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfire weather is analyzed through variables such as wind, precipitation,
 air temperature, and relative humidity.
 The behaviour of this meteorological variables influences every aspect
 of bushfires, including their start, spread and intensity.
 Bushfires start if high temperatures, low levels of relative humidity and
 precipitation have dried vegetation to a flammable point.
 Winds also contribute in the ignition of bushfires by taking moisture content
 out of the vegetation and providing oxygen for combustion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, atmospheric instability favours the occurence of thunderstorms;
 which are a natural ignition source of bushfires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 The spread of bushfires is controlled by winds, which propagate them and
 also can change their flank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 Atmospheric instability also contributes to the spread of these events
 because it produces spotting (spotfires).
 The intensity of bushfires is determined by the flammability and distribution
 of vegetation; which are controlled by precipitation in seasonal time scales
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Synoptics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The meteorological variables of bushfire weather are governed by large-scale
 synoptic patterns that have particular characteristics in different regions
 of Australia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 However, the synoptic weather patterns associated with bushfires all have
 hot-dry air advection processes in common, and often the passage of cold
 fronts in initiated bushfire areas 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 For example, bushfire weather in southeast Australia is characterized by
 an atmospheric high-pressure centre (“high”) in the Tasman Sea and a strong
 cold front arriving from the west 
