\begin_layout Subsubsection
Keet-Byram Drought Index (KBDI)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index was developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KeetchJJ"

\end_inset

 for the U.S Department of Agriculture-Forest Service, which originally used
 an 8 inches (approximately 200 mm) layer of soil for evaluation, yielding
 an index that ranges from 0 to 800.
 A zero value represents saturation and eight hundred is the highest possible
 value of dryness for a soil.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fundamental variables for the calculation of this index are rainfall
 and maximum temperature.
 The index can only be calculated for areas where the mean annual rainfall
 is known; additionally, the information of the 24 hours past rainfall is
 a fundamental requirement for the computation.
 Temperature is a key factor of evapotranspiration that is incorporated
 in the physical theory of soil moisture depletion used for the elaboration
 of the index.
\end_layout

