\begin_layout Subsubsection
Indian Ocean Dipole
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Indian Ocean Dipole (IOD) is another coupled ocean-atmosphere physical
 process.
 This process is characterized by cool sea surface temperatures in Sumatra
 and warmer than average SST in the western side of the Indian Ocean basin.
 This dipole structure explains 12% of the variance in sea suface temperature
 in this region.
 This is a process independent of the El Nino-Southern Oscillation, although
 this is a matter of ongoing debate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the mechanisms that drive both events are similar.
 The IOD process starts with the cooling of SST in Sumatra.
 A wekenning—or even reversal—of the westerly winds close to sea surface
 enhances the SST warming in the west side of the Indian Ocean basin.
 The warm SST produce convection, which drives precipitation over eastern
 Africa.
 The hot and moist air produce by the convection process travel on a westerly
 direction.
 On the upper troposphere the air mass dries and cools, and then sinks over
 Sumatra.
 The subsidence of these air masses produce drought conditions over Indonesia.
 The entire proces starts in May and peaks in October.
 
\end_layout

